WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.030


00:00:08.030 --> 00:00:09.890
- A government report released this week

00:00:09.890 --> 00:00:13.880
warns of an alarming rise in sea levels in the years to come.

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:15.050
Here's one statistic.

00:00:15.050 --> 00:00:19.670
Over the past 100 years, the sea level rose by about a foot.

00:00:19.670 --> 00:00:22.430
But now, new estimates say that same increase

00:00:22.430 --> 00:00:26.180
is likely to happen in just the next three decades.

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:28.970
This shift is projected to bring about more flooding

00:00:28.970 --> 00:00:31.370
and financial hardship across the country.

00:00:31.370 --> 00:00:35.090
And the effects could spill well beyond coastal communities.

00:00:35.090 --> 00:00:38.940
NOAA administrator Rick Spinrad joins me now for more.

00:00:38.940 --> 00:00:41.570
He is also the Undersecretary of Commerce

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:43.520
for Oceans and Atmosphere.

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:44.300
Rick, welcome.

00:00:44.300 --> 00:00:45.770
It's so great to have you with us.

00:00:45.770 --> 00:00:49.260
Break down this report your agency helped put together,

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:49.850
if you will.

00:00:49.850 --> 00:00:51.440
What are the key takeaways?

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:53.960
And what exactly is leading to these rising sea levels?

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:58.870
Is it all attributable to global warming and carbon emissions?

00:00:58.870 --> 00:01:00.160
RICK SPINRAD: Thank you, Tanya.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:02.470
Yeah, this report is particularly significant,

00:01:02.470 --> 00:01:06.700
largely because of the accuracy of the information contained

00:01:06.700 --> 00:01:07.990
therein.

00:01:07.990 --> 00:01:11.600
And the relevance to public safety and the economy.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:15.040
So the rise in sea level is basically

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:19.150
attributable to melting ice places like Greenland

00:01:19.150 --> 00:01:23.410
and Antarctica, coupled with just the expansion of water

00:01:23.410 --> 00:01:24.610
when it gets warmer.

00:01:24.610 --> 00:01:26.170
And the third factor, and the reason

00:01:26.170 --> 00:01:28.180
why it's slightly different in the Gulf

00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:30.250
than it might be on the East Coast or West Coast,

00:01:30.250 --> 00:01:34.070
is because the land movement changes as well.

00:01:34.070 --> 00:01:36.070
So in the Gulf where we've got subsidence,

00:01:36.070 --> 00:01:39.250
you see a little bit higher sea level rise compared

00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:40.840
to places like the West Coast.

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:44.950
And the main value, if you will, of this particular report

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:46.900
is you can take it to the bank.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:50.800
This sea level rise is going to affect everything

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:54.310
from infrastructure to property costs and property values.

00:01:54.310 --> 00:01:58.870
And so consequently the accuracy of the forecast information

00:01:58.870 --> 00:02:01.090
here can be used by local communities

00:02:01.090 --> 00:02:02.410
to rebuild infrastructure.

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:04.330
Can be used by insurance companies.

00:02:04.330 --> 00:02:06.820
It's basically a way for us to become

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:12.050
much more resilient in our adaptation to climate change.

00:02:12.050 --> 00:02:15.160
- So you're saying we over the next 30 years

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:18.610
that the sea levels will rise about a foot, right?

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:21.310
That's knowledge that we can take to the bank, as you said.

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:22.790
Is that correct?

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:23.830
RICK SPINRAD: Absolutely.

00:02:23.830 --> 00:02:26.440
That's the real main takeaway from this particular report.

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:29.210
In the past, we've had a broader range of predictions.

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:31.510
But now the science is so good and the predictions

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:35.650
are so skillful that we can comfortably and accurately say

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:39.980
10 to 12 inches of sea level rise will be seen by 2050.

00:02:39.980 --> 00:02:41.410
- So Rick, talk to us a little bit

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:42.790
about the pace we're seeing here.

00:02:42.790 --> 00:02:45.130
Because this represents a significant increase

00:02:45.130 --> 00:02:48.610
to what we've seen over the past 100 years, doesn't it?

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:50.730
RICK SPINRAD: Yeah, in fact, the changes that we'll

00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:52.940
see in the next 30 years are equivalent to what we've

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:54.670
seen in the last 100 years.

00:02:54.670 --> 00:02:58.140
This 10 to 12 inch rise in sea level

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:00.090
is what we saw over the last century.

00:03:00.090 --> 00:03:03.120
And what it means is that we've got to start planning now.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:04.810
We've got to take this information,

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:06.780
use it to help guide decisions.

00:03:06.780 --> 00:03:10.440
The Biden administration is leaning forward aggressively

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:12.270
on making sure we reduce emissions,

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:14.970
we start making better use of renewable energy.

00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:16.350
And that all has to happen.

00:03:16.350 --> 00:03:19.590
At the same time, we've got to be adapting and becoming

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:22.080
resilient to the changes we know will be coming

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:23.860
in the next couple of decades.

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:28.620
So this increase in sea level, the rise of 10 to 12 inches,

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:30.630
will actually result in the flooding

00:03:30.630 --> 00:03:35.410
of about 2,700 square miles of our coastlines right now.

00:03:35.410 --> 00:03:39.480
And so starting now, building out now, planning now,

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:42.810
is what this clarion call of sea level rise

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:44.690
means to us as a society.

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:47.190
- And to your point that we have to start preparing for what

00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:48.330
we know is going to happen, let's

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:50.820
talk a little bit about the impact on coastal communities

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:51.810
and beyond.

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:53.820
How will this change their everyday lives

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:55.840
economically and otherwise?

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:59.460
And what could the domino effect be on the rest of the country?

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:00.250
RICK SPINRAD: Yeah.

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:02.860
Think about what coastal communities are facing right

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:05.740
now with respect to rebuilding or changing

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:06.610
their infrastructure.

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:10.390
Everything from roads to water treatment plants

00:04:10.390 --> 00:04:11.920
to the electrical grid.

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:13.990
Not to mention at the individual level

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:15.850
the costs of property and houses.

00:04:15.850 --> 00:04:18.380
And the threats to the safety of the individuals.

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:21.040
And so all of these factors of our lives

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:22.340
are going to be affected.

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:25.060
And by taking advantage of this information now,

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:28.150
we can ensure that we're saving and we're protecting

00:04:28.150 --> 00:04:30.290
lives and protecting property.

00:04:30.290 --> 00:04:33.490
As for the rest of the country, if you will,

00:04:33.490 --> 00:04:37.810
it's important to recognize that 95% of our imported

00:04:37.810 --> 00:04:40.120
goods in this country come through the ports

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:40.960
along our coasts.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:44.290
And so if we're not starting to address the infrastructure

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:48.640
needs in the ports right now because of sea level rise,

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:51.130
we will be challenging our ability

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:53.260
to make sure those imports can get through

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:57.670
to the consumers and users swiftly and effectively.

00:04:57.670 --> 00:05:01.060
At NOAA, we're trying to do this across the board for any number

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:03.730
of impacts from climate change through something we're calling

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:05.530
the Climate Ready Nation.

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:07.990
And this sea level rise report is

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:10.690
part of our effort to help ensure a climate ready Nation.

00:05:10.690 --> 00:05:12.190
- And Rick, of course we know what's

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:13.850
going to happen over the next three decades,

00:05:13.850 --> 00:05:15.370
but we need to look forward, as you said.

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:17.160
Because we obviously don't want to see this

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:18.470
continue at this pace.

00:05:18.470 --> 00:05:20.800
So what realistically needs to be done to change course?

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:25.120
You mentioned some of the Biden administration's initiatives.

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:28.590
But is it not too late for meaningful action?

00:05:28.590 --> 00:05:30.760
RICK SPINRAD: We can take a lot of action right now.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:32.340
And that's why we're excited about how

00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:34.670
the bipartisan infrastructure law that was just

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:36.250
signed by the President a little while

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:39.880
back can be used immediately to start addressing things

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:42.490
like hardening port infrastructure,

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:44.260
rethinking how we're building out

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:47.420
our roads and our electrical infrastructure.

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:49.360
That's what we can start doing right now.

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:51.610
Meantime, in the longer term, looking

00:05:51.610 --> 00:05:54.070
at reductions of carbon emissions

00:05:54.070 --> 00:05:56.770
is a way to ensure that we don't face the worst case

00:05:56.770 --> 00:06:00.220
scenario by the end of this century, for example.

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:02.230
- Rick Spinrad, NOAA administrator.

00:06:02.230 --> 00:06:03.650
Thank you so much for joining us.

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:05.930
We appreciate your time.

00:06:05.930 --> 00:06:07.620
RICK SPINRAD: Thank you.